import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Nav from '../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="Constitution of The Grace Network — Founding Document"
  description="The founding constitution of The Grace Network: a network state movement for AI safety, radical transparency, scientific governance, and universal flourishing in the age of intelligence."
  image="https://sethgoldstein.com/party/og-grace-network.svg"
>
  <!-- Navigation -->
  <Nav currentPath="/constitution" />

  <!-- Constitution Header -->
  <header class="const-header">
    <div class="const-header-content">
      <div class="const-badge">FOUNDING DOCUMENT</div>
      <h1>The Constitution</h1>
      <p class="const-subtitle">of The Grace Network</p>
      <div class="const-ornament">
        <svg width="200" height="20" viewBox="0 0 200 20" fill="none">
          <line x1="0" y1="10" x2="80" y2="10" stroke="#8B5CF6" stroke-width="0.5" opacity="0.4"/>
          <circle cx="100" cy="10" r="4" fill="#D97706" opacity="0.8"/>
          <line x1="120" y1="10" x2="200" y2="10" stroke="#8B5CF6" stroke-width="0.5" opacity="0.4"/>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <p class="const-epigraph">
        "We do not inherit the future from our predecessors — we build it,<br/>
        deliberately, responsibly, and with grace."
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- Main Constitution Body -->
  <div class="const-layout">
    <!-- Table of Contents Sidebar -->
    <aside class="toc-sidebar" id="tocSidebar">
      <div class="toc-inner">
        <div class="toc-title">TABLE OF CONTENTS</div>
        <nav class="toc-nav">
          <a href="#preamble" class="toc-link">Preamble</a>
          <a href="#article-i" class="toc-link">Article I <span>Name &amp; Nature</span></a>
          <a href="#article-ii" class="toc-link">Article II <span>Founding Principles</span></a>
          <a href="#article-iii" class="toc-link">Article III <span>Rights of Members</span></a>
          <a href="#article-iv" class="toc-link">Article IV <span>Governance Structure</span></a>
          <a href="#article-v" class="toc-link">Article V <span>Network State Roadmap</span></a>
          <a href="#article-vi" class="toc-link">Article VI <span>Amendments</span></a>
          <a href="#article-vii" class="toc-link">Article VII <span>Ratification</span></a>
        </nav>
        <div class="toc-divider"></div>
        <a href="/#sign" class="toc-cta">Sign the Constitution</a>
      </div>
    </aside>

    <!-- Constitution Content -->
    <main class="const-content">

      <!-- Preamble -->
      <section class="const-section" id="preamble">
        <div class="section-ornament">
          <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 40 40" fill="none">
            <circle cx="20" cy="20" r="18" stroke="#8B5CF6" stroke-width="0.75" opacity="0.3"/>
            <circle cx="20" cy="20" r="10" stroke="#8B5CF6" stroke-width="0.75" opacity="0.5"/>
            <circle cx="20" cy="20" r="3" fill="#D97706" opacity="0.9"/>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <h2 class="preamble-heading">Preamble</h2>
        <div class="preamble-text">
          <p class="preamble-drop">
            We stand at the threshold of the most transformative era in human history. Artificial intelligence — a technology of extraordinary power and consequence — will reshape every aspect of civilization: how we govern, how we heal, how we learn, how we create, how we relate to one another, and how we understand ourselves. Within our lifetimes, the decisions made about the development, deployment, and governance of these systems will determine whether humanity enters an age of unprecedented flourishing or one of catastrophic fragmentation.
          </p>
          <p>
            We choose to meet this moment not with fear, not with recklessness, but with <em>grace</em> — a word we define as the union of responsible development, democratic governance, and the unwavering conviction that abundance can and must cascade to all. We reject the false dichotomy between progress and safety, between innovation and equity, between the power of technology and the dignity of humanity. We choose all of it.
          </p>
          <p>
            We are citizens of the digital age, and we recognize that the political institutions inherited from centuries past — forged for a world of scarcity, geography, and slow communication — are insufficient for governing a world of abundance, networks, and instantaneous connection. And so we build anew: a political community organized not around arbitrary borders but around shared moral conviction, not around coercion but around voluntary alignment, not around ideology but around evidence and empathy.
          </p>
          <p>
            We, the founding members of <strong>The Grace Network</strong>, do hereby establish this Constitution as the supreme governing document of our community — a covenant among aligned minds, a declaration of principles, and a living framework for the governance of a new kind of nation.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Article I -->
      <section class="const-section" id="article-i">
        <div class="article-marker">ARTICLE I</div>
        <h2>Name and Nature</h2>
        <div class="article-body">
          <p>
            This political community shall be known as <strong>The Grace Network</strong> — taking its name from the vision of a future where powerful technology is developed with care, deployed with wisdom, and governed with the grace that dignifies both creator and creation. The name invokes the aspiration that machines of extraordinary capability might serve as instruments of profound human benefit — machines of loving grace.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Grace Network is constituted as a <strong>network state</strong>: a digital-first political community organized as a voluntary association of aligned individuals who share a moral vision for the age of intelligence. It is a sovereign community in the tradition articulated by the network state movement — beginning as an online community united by shared values, growing into a network capable of collective action, and aspiring toward eventual diplomatic recognition as a legitimate polity.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Grace Network is not bound by geography, ethnicity, or inherited citizenship. Membership is volitional and value-aligned. Our territory is, first, the digital commons — the protocols, platforms, and encrypted channels through which we deliberate, decide, and act. In time, it may extend to physical spaces: crowdfunded land, coworking nodes, residential enclaves, and embassies of aligned presence in the physical world. But always, the cloud comes first and the land comes last.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Article II -->
      <section class="const-section" id="article-ii">
        <div class="article-marker">ARTICLE II</div>
        <h2>Founding Principles</h2>
        <p class="article-intro">
          The Grace Network is founded upon seven inviolable principles. These principles are not merely aspirational — they are constitutional commitments that constrain and guide every decision, policy, and action undertaken in the name of this community.
        </p>

        <div class="principle" id="principle-1">
          <div class="principle-header">
            <span class="principle-num">I</span>
            <h3>Safety-First Progress</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="principle-body">
            <p>
              We hold that the responsible development of powerful technology is not merely a preference but a moral imperative. Every advance in capability must be matched — and preceded — by a corresponding advance in safety, interpretability, and control. We do not release what we cannot understand, and we do not deploy what we cannot constrain.
            </p>
            <p>
              This principle is drawn from the practice of responsible scaling: the discipline of establishing clear safety benchmarks, testing rigorously against them, and refusing to cross capability thresholds without demonstrated safety assurances. We apply this logic not only to AI systems but to all governance decisions. The precautionary principle is not an obstacle to progress — it is the very foundation of durable progress.
            </p>
            <p>
              In governance, safety-first means that no policy shall be implemented at scale without first being tested in controlled conditions. We pilot before we legislate. We measure before we mandate. And we retain the humility to reverse course when evidence demands it.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="principle" id="principle-2">
          <div class="principle-header">
            <span class="principle-num">II</span>
            <h3>Universal Flourishing</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="principle-body">
            <p>
              The benefits of transformative technology must cascade to all of humanity — not pool at the apex of wealth and power. We believe that AI-driven breakthroughs in medicine, education, scientific discovery, and economic productivity represent an opportunity without precedent: the chance to solve problems that have plagued civilization since its inception. Disease. Ignorance. Poverty. Isolation. These are not immutable features of the human condition — they are engineering problems, and we intend to solve them.
            </p>
            <p>
              Universal flourishing is not charity; it is architecture. We design systems, policies, and incentive structures so that prosperity compounds and distributes by default. When a medical AI discovers a new treatment, the default is global access, not exclusive licensing. When an educational AI personalizes learning, the default is universal availability, not premium subscription. Abundance is not a zero-sum game — it compounds when shared.
            </p>
            <p>
              We commit to measuring our success not by the prosperity of our most advantaged members, but by the material and spiritual well-being of our least advantaged. No community is truly flourishing until its most vulnerable members are thriving.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="principle" id="principle-3">
          <div class="principle-header">
            <span class="principle-num">III</span>
            <h3>Radical Transparency</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="principle-body">
            <p>
              Just as we demand interpretability in AI systems — the ability to understand why a model produces a given output — we demand interpretability in governance. Every policy decision, every budget allocation, every leadership action must have a legible rationale that any member can inspect, question, and challenge. Our governance is an open model, not a black box.
            </p>
            <p>
              Radical transparency means that all deliberations of The Assembly, all decisions of The Stewards, and all recommendations of The Council of Influences are documented, published, and permanently accessible. Voting records are public. Financial flows are auditable. The reasoning behind every significant decision is written down and made available before the decision takes effect.
            </p>
            <p>
              We recognize that transparency has limits — personal privacy, security-sensitive operations, and ongoing negotiations may require temporary confidentiality. But these exceptions are narrow, time-limited, and themselves subject to oversight. The default is open. Secrecy requires justification; transparency does not.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="principle" id="principle-4">
          <div class="principle-header">
            <span class="principle-num">IV</span>
            <h3>Digital Sovereignty</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="principle-body">
            <p>
              In the tradition of network states, The Grace Network is cloud-first and conviction-driven. Our community governs itself through digital-native institutions: smart social contracts, on-chain referenda, cryptographic identity, and programmable governance. We do not wait for legacy institutions to grant us permission to organize. We build the infrastructure of self-governance from the ground up.
            </p>
            <p>
              Digital sovereignty means that every member holds a verifiable, cryptographic identity within the network. It means that our census is on-chain and auditable. It means that our governance tools — voting, deliberation, treasury management — are built on protocols that no single entity controls. And it means that our community can function, coordinate, and make binding decisions regardless of the political geography in which our members reside.
            </p>
            <p>
              We begin as a digital nation — a community of shared values, connected by protocol, governed by code and covenant. In time, we aim to acquire physical territory, establish nodes of embodied community, and seek diplomatic recognition. But our sovereignty is not contingent on land. It is contingent on alignment, on participation, and on the mutual commitment of our members to one another.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="principle" id="principle-5">
          <div class="principle-header">
            <span class="principle-num">V</span>
            <h3>Scientific Governance</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="principle-body">
            <p>
              Policy should be evidence-based, not ideology-driven. We adopt the scientific method for governance: hypothesize, test, measure, iterate. We do not pass laws on the basis of intuition, tribal affiliation, or rhetorical persuasion alone. We pass policies that have been tested, measured, and shown to produce the outcomes we intend.
            </p>
            <p>
              Scientific governance means we run policy pilots before we mandate at scale. We publish results — including failures — with the same rigor expected of peer-reviewed research. We pre-register policy hypotheses, define success metrics in advance, and commit to follow-through evaluation. Governance is too important for dogma — it deserves the rigor we give to research.
            </p>
            <p>
              This principle also demands epistemic humility. We will be wrong. Our models of the world will be incomplete. Our policies will have unintended consequences. And when that happens, we do not double down out of pride — we update our beliefs, revise our approaches, and communicate honestly about what we have learned. A governance system that cannot admit error is a governance system destined to fail.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="principle" id="principle-6">
          <div class="principle-header">
            <span class="principle-num">VI</span>
            <h3>Aligned Incentives</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="principle-body">
            <p>
              Inspired by the discipline of Constitutional AI — the practice of embedding human values directly into the training and behavior of AI systems — we embed alignment directly into our institutions. Power structures are designed so that the incentives of leaders and citizens converge. When representatives succeed, the network succeeds. When the network prospers, every member benefits. Misalignment is treated as a systemic risk — we engineer against it the way we engineer against unsafe AI.
            </p>
            <p>
              Aligned incentives mean that no leader can profit from decisions that harm the community. Compensation structures, term limits, recall mechanisms, and transparency requirements are designed to make self-dealing structurally difficult and personally costly. Our constitution is, in effect, a set of alignment constraints on the behavior of governance — just as a constitutional AI's training ensures it serves human values rather than its own optimization targets.
            </p>
            <p>
              We further commit to ongoing alignment audits: regular, independent reviews of whether our governance structures are producing outcomes consistent with our stated principles. If drift is detected — if incentives have become misaligned, if power has concentrated, if transparency has eroded — the audit triggers mandatory reform. Alignment is not a one-time achievement; it is a continuous practice.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="principle" id="principle-7">
          <div class="principle-header">
            <span class="principle-num">VII</span>
            <h3>Cascading Abundance</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="principle-body">
            <p>
              We believe in a future where artificial intelligence cures diseases that have haunted humanity for millennia, where education is personalized to the needs and pace of every learner, where scientific discovery accelerates beyond what any prior generation could have imagined, and where economic abundance cascades across every stratum of society. This is not utopia — it is an engineering problem. And we intend to solve it, carefully, responsibly, and with grace.
            </p>
            <p>
              Cascading abundance is the ultimate measure of our success. It means that the breakthroughs generated within and around our community flow outward — from early adopters to the global population, from the technologically fluent to the technologically underserved, from the wealthy to the impoverished. We build not for ourselves alone but for the billions who have not yet heard of us and may never join our ranks.
            </p>
            <p>
              This principle demands that we resist the temptation to hoard. Knowledge is shared. Tools are open-sourced where safe to do so. Health innovations are priced for access, not extraction. Educational resources are freely available. The measure of abundance is not what we accumulate — it is what we release into the world. The cascade is the point.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Article III -->
      <section class="const-section" id="article-iii">
        <div class="article-marker">ARTICLE III</div>
        <h2>Rights of Members</h2>
        <p class="article-intro">
          Every member of The Grace Network is endowed with the following inalienable rights. These rights are not granted by the community — they are recognized by it. They exist prior to and independent of any governance structure, and no act of The Assembly, The Stewards, or The Council may abridge them.
        </p>

        <div class="rights-list">
          <div class="right-item">
            <div class="right-marker">
              <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none">
                <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10" stroke="#8B5CF6" stroke-width="1"/>
                <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="3" fill="#D97706"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="right-content">
              <h4>The Right to Exit</h4>
              <p>
                Membership in The Grace Network is voluntary, always and absolutely. No member may be compelled to remain, and no penalty — financial, social, or reputational — shall attach to the decision to leave. The right to exit is the foundational check on power: a community that cannot be left is not a community but a prison. Any member may withdraw at any time, for any reason, with full portability of their personal data and a fair accounting of any shared assets.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="right-item">
            <div class="right-marker">
              <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none">
                <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10" stroke="#8B5CF6" stroke-width="1"/>
                <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="3" fill="#D97706"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="right-content">
              <h4>The Right to Transparency</h4>
              <p>
                Every member has the right to a complete and comprehensible account of how the community is governed. All policy decisions, financial transactions, and governance proceedings shall be documented and made accessible. No member shall be bound by a decision whose rationale is hidden. The right to transparency is the right to informed consent — and without informed consent, governance is mere authority.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="right-item">
            <div class="right-marker">
              <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none">
                <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10" stroke="#8B5CF6" stroke-width="1"/>
                <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="3" fill="#D97706"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="right-content">
              <h4>The Right to Voice</h4>
              <p>
                Every member has the right to participate in deliberation on any matter affecting the community. This includes the right to propose policy, to speak in Assembly, to vote on referenda, and to challenge decisions through established channels. Voice is not merely the right to speak — it is the right to be heard, to receive a reasoned response, and to have one's perspective genuinely weighed in the calculus of collective decision-making.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="right-item">
            <div class="right-marker">
              <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none">
                <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10" stroke="#8B5CF6" stroke-width="1"/>
                <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="3" fill="#D97706"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="right-content">
              <h4>The Right to Benefit</h4>
              <p>
                Every member has the right to share in the collective prosperity of the network. As the community generates value — through technology, governance innovation, cooperative enterprise, or collective investment — that value shall be distributed equitably. No class of members shall be structurally excluded from the material benefits of participation. Prosperity is a shared project, and its fruits must be shared fruits.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="right-item">
            <div class="right-marker">
              <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none">
                <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10" stroke="#8B5CF6" stroke-width="1"/>
                <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="3" fill="#D97706"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="right-content">
              <h4>The Right to Privacy</h4>
              <p>
                Every member has the right to privacy in their personal affairs, communications, and data. The Grace Network shall not surveil, monitor, or collect personal information beyond what is strictly necessary for governance functions — and even that collection requires informed, revocable consent. Privacy is not a concession — it is a precondition for the dignity and autonomy upon which voluntary association depends.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="right-item">
            <div class="right-marker">
              <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none">
                <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10" stroke="#8B5CF6" stroke-width="1"/>
                <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="3" fill="#D97706"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="right-content">
              <h4>The Right to Meaning</h4>
              <p>
                Every member has the right to a community that serves human dignity, not one that replaces it. Technology is a tool for human flourishing, not a substitute for human purpose. The Grace Network commits to ensuring that automation augments rather than erases meaningful work, that algorithmic decision-making supports rather than supplants human judgment in matters of moral consequence, and that the pursuit of efficiency never comes at the cost of the irreducible value of human experience, creativity, and connection.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Article IV -->
      <section class="const-section" id="article-iv">
        <div class="article-marker">ARTICLE IV</div>
        <h2>Governance Structure</h2>
        <p class="article-intro">
          The governance of The Grace Network is designed for alignment, transparency, and adaptability. Power is distributed across multiple bodies, each with defined authority and accountability, each checked by the others and by the rights of individual members.
        </p>

        <div class="gov-body">
          <div class="gov-body-header">
            <div class="gov-icon">
              <svg width="48" height="48" viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none">
                <circle cx="24" cy="24" r="20" stroke="#8B5CF6" stroke-width="1.5"/>
                <circle cx="24" cy="14" r="4" fill="#D97706" opacity="0.8"/>
                <circle cx="14" cy="30" r="4" fill="#D97706" opacity="0.8"/>
                <circle cx="34" cy="30" r="4" fill="#D97706" opacity="0.8"/>
                <circle cx="24" cy="24" r="6" stroke="#8B5CF6" stroke-width="1"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <h3>The Assembly</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="gov-body-content">
            <p>
              The Assembly comprises all members of The Grace Network. It is the sovereign deliberative body — the ultimate source of political authority within the community. All members have equal standing in The Assembly, regardless of tenure, contribution, or status.
            </p>
            <p>
              The Assembly holds the exclusive power to ratify constitutional amendments, approve the annual governance budget, elect and recall Stewards, and declare positions on matters of collective concern. Deliberation in The Assembly takes place through both synchronous forums (scheduled sessions with structured debate) and asynchronous channels (written proposals, commentary periods, and digital voting).
            </p>
            <p>
              Quorum for Assembly decisions is defined as participation by no less than twenty percent of active members, with "active" defined as having engaged in at least one governance action in the preceding ninety days. Ordinary resolutions pass by simple majority; matters of constitutional significance require the supermajority thresholds defined in Article VI.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gov-body">
          <div class="gov-body-header">
            <div class="gov-icon">
              <svg width="48" height="48" viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none">
                <rect x="8" y="8" width="32" height="32" rx="4" stroke="#D97706" stroke-width="1.5"/>
                <circle cx="18" cy="20" r="3" fill="#8B5CF6" opacity="0.8"/>
                <circle cx="30" cy="20" r="3" fill="#8B5CF6" opacity="0.8"/>
                <circle cx="24" cy="32" r="3" fill="#8B5CF6" opacity="0.8"/>
                <line x1="18" y1="23" x2="24" y2="29" stroke="#8B5CF6" stroke-width="0.75" opacity="0.5"/>
                <line x1="30" y1="23" x2="24" y2="29" stroke="#8B5CF6" stroke-width="0.75" opacity="0.5"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <h3>The Council of Influences</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="gov-body-content">
            <p>
              The Council of Influences is the moral and intellectual compass of The Grace Network. It is composed of thinkers — both living and historical — whose ideas, writings, and principles serve as guiding references for community deliberation. The Council does not hold executive or legislative power; its authority is persuasive, not coercive.
            </p>
            <p>
              Living members of the Council may be invited to address The Assembly, review policy proposals, and contribute written guidance. Historical figures on the Council serve as canonical references: their works are studied, cited, and drawn upon as intellectual foundations for governance decisions. The Council is not a body of rulers but a constellation of wisdom — a curated library of aligned thought.
            </p>
            <p>
              Membership in the Council is proposed by any member of The Assembly and ratified by a two-thirds vote. Council members serve in an advisory capacity and may not simultaneously hold the office of Steward. The Council publishes an annual letter to the community reflecting on the state of alignment between governance practice and founding principles.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gov-body">
          <div class="gov-body-header">
            <div class="gov-icon">
              <svg width="48" height="48" viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none">
                <path d="M24 8L40 18v12L24 40 8 30V18L24 8z" stroke="#8B5CF6" stroke-width="1.5"/>
                <circle cx="24" cy="24" r="8" fill="#D97706" opacity="0.1"/>
                <circle cx="24" cy="24" r="4" fill="#D97706" opacity="0.6"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <h3>The Stewards</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="gov-body-content">
            <p>
              The Stewards are the elected operational leaders of The Grace Network, responsible for executing the will of The Assembly, managing community resources, and representing the network in external affairs. Stewards are elected by ranked-choice vote of The Assembly for terms of two years, with a maximum of two consecutive terms.
            </p>
            <p>
              Stewards are bound by a strict code of conduct rooted in the principle of aligned incentives. Their compensation is tied to community-defined outcome metrics, and they are subject to continuous transparency requirements including public calendars, decision logs, and quarterly accountability sessions before The Assembly. Any Steward may be recalled by a two-thirds vote of The Assembly at any time.
            </p>
            <p>
              The body of Stewards is intentionally small — no more than seven at any time — to preserve accountability and prevent bureaucratic expansion. Each Steward holds a defined portfolio (e.g., Safety and Policy, Community Development, Treasury, External Relations), and decisions of the Stewards require majority agreement among their number.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gov-body">
          <div class="gov-body-header">
            <div class="gov-icon">
              <svg width="48" height="48" viewBox="0 0 48 48" fill="none">
                <circle cx="24" cy="24" r="20" stroke="#8B5CF6" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="4 4"/>
                <path d="M24 12v24M16 20l8-8 8 8" stroke="#D97706" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <h3>Constitutional Review</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="gov-body-content">
            <p>
              This Constitution is a living document, but it is not a casual one. Amendments may be proposed by any member and require the process defined in Article VI — including supermajority approval and a mandatory cooling-off period — to ensure that changes to the foundational compact are deliberate, considered, and broadly supported.
            </p>
            <p>
              A Constitutional Review Board, composed of three members elected by The Assembly and two appointed by the Council of Influences, is charged with interpreting constitutional provisions when disputes arise, reviewing proposed amendments for internal consistency, and publishing an annual assessment of constitutional health — identifying areas where practice has diverged from principle and recommending corrective action.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gov-body">
          <div class="gov-body-header">
            <div class="gov-icon">
